<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Regular Polygon</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Polygons/RegularPolygon.=
nb" download=3D"RegularPolygon.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" alt=
=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"471.557" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/RegularPolygons_800.svg" class=3D=
"" alt=3D"RegularPolygons">
</div>
<p>
A regular polygon is an <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/RegularPolygon/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-he=
ight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">=
-sided
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Polygon.html">polygon</a> in whic=
h the sides are all the same length and
 are symmetrically placed about a common center (i.e., the polygon is both =
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquiangularPolygon.html">equiangul=
ar</a>
 and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquilateralPolygon.html">equi=
lateral</a>). Only certain regular polygons
 are "<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConstructiblePolygon.html">c=
onstructible</a>" using the
 classical Greek tools of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Comp=
ass.html">compass</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Straight=
edge.html">straightedge</a>.
</p>
<p>
The terms <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquilateralTriangle.html=
">equilateral triangle</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Squ=
are.html">square</a> refer to the regular 3- and 4-polygons, respectively. =
The words for <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Polygon.html">polygo=
ns</a>
 with <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/RegularPol=
ygon/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n&gt;=3D5">
 sides (e.g., <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pentagon.html">penta=
gon</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Hexagon.html">hexagon</a>=
,
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Heptagon.html">heptagon</a>, etc.=
) can refer to either regular or non-regular
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Polygon.html">polygons</a>, altho=
ugh the terms generally refer to regular
 polygons in the absence of specific wording.
</p>
<p>
A regular <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Regula=
rPolygon/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">-gon
 is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram=
 Language</a>
 as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/RegularPolygon=
.html">RegularPolygon</a></tt>[<i>n</i>],
 or more generally as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/=
ref/RegularPolygon.html">RegularPolygon</a></tt>[<i>r</i>,
 <i>n</i>], <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Regula=
rPolygon.html">RegularPolygon</a></tt>[<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/RegularPolygon/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D=
"21" alt=3D"{"><i>x</i>, <i>y</i><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
images/equations/RegularPolygon/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D"21" =
alt=3D"}">, <i>rspec</i>, <i>n</i>], etc.
</p>
<p>
The sum of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Perpendicular.html">per=
